# Start of question: When is diffraction an important effect?
:TYPE:MC:1:0:C
:TITLE:When is diffraction an important effect?
:FEEDBACK:H

:QUESTION:H
Under what conditions is diffraction an important effect (i.e. under what conditions do we see it)?
:IMAGE:
:LAYOUT:vertical
:ANSWERORDER:randomized
:INDICES:letters
:ANSWER1:100:H
when a wave of any sort passes through an opening that is comparable in size to the wavelength
:ANSWER2:0:H
with water waves and other 2 or 3-D mechanical waves but not with light or sound.
:ANSWER3:0:H
with light or sound but not with water waves or other 2 or 3-D mechanical waves.
:ANSWER4:0:H
when a wave of any sort passes through an opening that is comparable in size to the amplitude
:ANSWER5:0:H
when a wave of any sort passes through an opening less than about 1/10 of a millimeter
:CAT:Wave Optics
# End of question: When is diffraction an important effect?

# Start of question: how does an interferometer work?
:TYPE:MC:1:0:C
:TITLE:how does an interferometer work?
:FEEDBACK:H

:QUESTION:H
A Michelson interferometer produces interference fringes by
:IMAGE:
:LAYOUT:vertical
:ANSWERORDER:randomized
:INDICES:letters
:ANSWER1:100:H
splitting the light, passing the two beams through different distances and recombining them on a screen.
:ANSWER2:0:H
passing the light through a diffraction grating.
:ANSWER3:0:H
passing the light through a double slit.
:ANSWER4:0:H
combining light from two different sources.
:ANSWER5:0:H
creating a standing wave in a light beam.
:CAT:Wave Optics
# End of question: how does an interferometer work?

# Start of question: light of two wavelengths through diffraction grating
:TYPE:MC:1:0:C
:TITLE:light of two wavelengths through diffraction grating
:FEEDBACK:H

:QUESTION:H
Light of two different colours passes through a diffraction grating.  On the screen behind the grating you will see
:IMAGE:
:LAYOUT:vertical
:ANSWERORDER:randomized
:INDICES:letters
:ANSWER1:100:H
two interference patterns with different spacings - one in each colour of light that was passed through the grating.
:ANSWER2:0:H
one interference pattern in a colour that is the combination of the of the two colours of light that passed through the grating.
:ANSWER3:0:H
nothing (the two light beams will interfere and cancel each other out).
:ANSWER4:0:H
a complicated rainbow-like pattern.
:CAT:Wave Optics
# End of question: light of two wavelengths through diffraction grating

# Start of question: pattern from large hole vs. pattern from pinhole
:TYPE:MC:1:0:C
:TITLE:pattern from large hole vs. pattern from pinhole
:FEEDBACK:H

:QUESTION:H
Light from a small, bright, single-wavelength lamp is passed through a
2.0 cm diameter hole and projected onto screen A. Light from the same
lamp is passed through a 0.1 mm pinhole onto screen B. What will be
seen on the screens?
:IMAGE:
:LAYOUT:vertical
:ANSWERORDER:randomized
:INDICES:letters
:ANSWER1:100:H
Screen A will show a sharp-edged, round spot of light but screen B
will show alternating rings of light and dark.
:ANSWER2:0:H
Both screens will show sharp edged, round spots of light.
:ANSWER3:0:H
Both screens will show alternating rings of light and dark.
:ANSWER4:0:H
Screen A will show alternating rings of light and dark but screen B
will show a sharp-edged, round spot of light.
:ANSWER5:0:H
Screen A will show a sharp-edged, round spot of light, but the light will be unable to pass through such a small pinhole so screen B will show nothing.
:CAT:Wave Optics
# End of question: pattern from large hole vs. pattern from pinhole

# Start of question: reason for interference from single slit
:TYPE:MC:1:0:C
:TITLE:reason for interference from single slit
:FEEDBACK:H

:QUESTION:H
Light passing through a single slit refracts (the wave fronts spread out behind the slit).  It produces an interference pattern because
:IMAGE:
:LAYOUT:vertical
:ANSWERORDER:randomized
:INDICES:letters
:ANSWER1:100:H
light leaving from anywhere in the slit can interfere with light half of the slit spacing away (a/2).
:ANSWER2:0:H
light leaving from one side of the slit interferes with light leaving from the other side of the slit.
:ANSWER3:0:H
the two sides of the slit act like two sources, just like a double slit would.
:ANSWER4:0:H
the light simply does not diffract through some angles so there are dark bands.
:CAT:Wave Optics
# End of question: reason for interference from single slit

# Start of question: effect of narrowing a single slit
:TYPE:MC:1:0:C
:TITLE:effect of narrowing a single slit
:FEEDBACK:H

:QUESTION:H
Light shines through a single, narrow, slit and produces a single slit interference pattern.  If the width of the slit were adjustable, what would happen to the interference pattern as you made the slit narrower?
:IMAGE:
:LAYOUT:vertical
:ANSWERORDER:randomized
:INDICES:letters
:ANSWER1:100:H
The fringes would move farther apart.
:ANSWER2:0:H
The fringes would move closer together.
:ANSWER3:0:H
The pattern would be unchanged.
:ANSWER4:0:H
The pattern would disappear.
:ANSWER5:0:H
It depends on the wavelength of the light.
:CAT:Wave Optics
# End of question: effect of narrowing a single slit

